Data Import

data <- readxl::read_xlsx("../data/HW_data.xlsx")

According to the provided description, we may assume that these variables possibly are associated with physical activity:

DRQSDT8 - Weight gain/Muscle building diet - we may suggest that people use this diet only in case when they workout DRQSDT10 - High protein diet - this kind of diet can be linked to active workout regime, this can be a part of inactive weight loosing program though PAQ605 - Vigorous work activity PAQ610 - Number of days vigorous work PAD615 - Minutes vigorous-intensity work - I suppose, this is the best factor reflecting physical activity at work, the factor is the most subjective though PAQ635 - Walk or bicycle PAQ640 - Number of days walk or bicycle PAD645 - Minutes walk/bicycle for transportation PAQ650 - Vigorous recreational activities PAQ655 - Days vigorous recreational activities PAD660 - Minutes vigorous recreational activities

Lets inspect them:

new_names <- c(

data %>% 
  select(
    DRQSDT8, DRQSDT10, PAQ605, PAQ610, PAD615, PAQ635,
    PAQ640, PAD645, PAQ650, PAQ655, PAD660
  ) %>% 
  rename_with(~ new_names) %>%
  mutate(across(-c(Walk.bicycle.min, Walk.bicycle.days, 
                 Vigorous.recr.min, Vigorous.recr.days,
                 Vigorous.work.min, Vigorous.work.days), as.factor)) %>% 
  ggpairs( 
  upper = list(continuous = wrap("points", alpha = 0.5, size = 1),
               combo = wrap("points", alpha = 0.5, size = 1),
               disrete = "blank"),
  lower = list(continuous = "cor",
               discrete = "count",
               combo = wrap("box_no_facet", outlier.size = 0.5)),
  diag = list(continuous = "barDiag",
              discrete = "barDiag"),
  showStrips = TRUE, progress = FALSE) +
  theme_bw(base_size = 7) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        strip.placement = "outside",
        strip.background = element_rect(color = "white", fill = "#EFEBE9"),
        strip.text = element_text(size = 7, face = "bold"))
